{"author":{"id":"2d08e4816aca0a07db9878f126b0e7f6d6f1362eb9bc4804be6b33ff8d0a19ec"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1728936709,"nonce":"/TLv5QT+Jq3lTdrIvcJ4We4y3QQ=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOJl1IZM6Pxf0Y","github-url":"https://github.com/nikitabobko/AeroSpace/issues/336#issuecomment-2412117272"},"message":"\u003e I don't know if there is any special reason for Aerospace don't use displayID as index for monitors\n\n@ggalves can you please point out to the specific `displayID` API? AeroSpace uses [`NSScreen` API](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nsscreen). And I don't anything about displayID in `NSScreen` docs\n\nAeroSpace uses own indexing method because:\n1. Apple API/docs don't say anything about order\n2. It's just logical to order monitors from left to right, top to bottom (AeroSpace sorts by `minX` and for every monitors with equal `minX` it sorts by `minY`). The same order is reflected in AeroSpace menu bar.\n\n\u003e developer of sketchybar responded with an information how monitors are indexed there\n\nThanks for the info! AFAIK, `SLSCopyManagedDisplays` is a private API in SkyLight private framework. And AeroSpace won't be using this API because of that.\n\nNevertheless, the order of monitors that people describe in this issue looks similar to what [NSScreen.screens](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nsscreen/1388393-screens) returns (main monitor goes first, all others go next enumerated from left to right). The docs only specify what is the first element of the array, so it's actually undefined in what order all others monitors go.\n\nI don't mind introducing `%{display-id}` in `--format` options as @ggalves suggests (though, I'd call it smth like `%{macos-native-monitor-id}` or `%{nsscreen-screens-monitor-id}`), but I'd like to first hear from @ggalves about the `displayID` API he was talking about\n\nAnd one last question: does sketchybar use 1-based or 0-based indices?","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1728936886,"nonce":"MZgjKZU4/saQBwV5w+OjqMrCpjs=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lALOJl1IZM6Pxf0YzlJG1UA"},"target":"8b12ff08da478137eb3929535916be615c53e6c04a76c1cfd2938f9f488450c6","message":"\u003e I don't know if there is any special reason for Aerospace don't use displayID as index for monitors\n\n@ggalves can you please point out to the specific `displayID` API? AeroSpace uses [`NSScreen` API](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nsscreen). And I don't anything about displayID in `NSScreen` docs\n\nAeroSpace uses own indexing method because:\n1. Apple API/docs don't say anything about order, so AeroSpace had to introduce it\n2. It's just logical to order monitors from left to right, top to bottom (AeroSpace sorts by `minX` and for every monitors with equal `minX` it sorts by `minY`). The same order is reflected in AeroSpace menu bar.\n\n\u003e developer of sketchybar responded with an information how monitors are indexed there\n\nThanks for the info! AFAIK, `SLSCopyManagedDisplays` is a private API in SkyLight private framework. And AeroSpace won't be using this API because of that.\n\nNevertheless, the order of monitors that people describe in this issue looks similar to what [NSScreen.screens](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nsscreen/1388393-screens) returns (main monitor goes first, all others go next enumerated from left to right). The docs only specify what is the first element of the array, so it's actually undefined in what order all others monitors go.\n\nI don't mind introducing `%{display-id}` in `--format` options as @ggalves suggests (though, I'd call it smth like `%{macos-native-monitor-id}` or `%{nsscreen-screens-monitor-id}`), but I'd like to first hear from @ggalves about the `displayID` API he was talking about\n\nAnd one last question: does sketchybar use 1-based or 0-based indices?","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1728936947,"nonce":"uQuVxWM7LT++jDLDeXhnIxicYbk=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lALOJl1IZM6Pxf0YzlJG2wg"},"target":"8b12ff08da478137eb3929535916be615c53e6c04a76c1cfd2938f9f488450c6","message":"\u003e I don't know if there is any special reason for Aerospace don't use displayID as index for monitors\n\n@ggalves can you please point out to the specific `displayID` API? AeroSpace uses [`NSScreen` API](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nsscreen). And I don't anything about displayID in `NSScreen` docs\n\nAeroSpace uses own indexing method because:\n1. Apple API/docs don't say anything about order, so AeroSpace had to introduce it\n2. It's just logical to order monitors from left to right, top to bottom (AeroSpace sorts by `minX` and for every monitors with equal `minX` it sorts by `minY`). The same order is reflected in AeroSpace menu bar.\n\n\u003e developer of sketchybar responded with an information how monitors are indexed there\n\nThanks for the info! AFAIK, `SLSCopyManagedDisplays` is a private API in SkyLight private framework. And AeroSpace won't be using this API because of that.\n\nNevertheless, the order of monitors that people describe in this issue looks similar to what [NSScreen.screens](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nsscreen/1388393-screens) returns (main monitor goes first, all others go next enumerated from left to right). The docs only specify what is the first element of the array, so it's actually undefined in what order all others monitors go.\n\nI don't mind introducing `%{display-id}` in `--format` options to use indices from `NSScreen.screens` as @ggalves suggests (though, I'd call it smth like `%{macos-native-monitor-id}` or `%{nsscreen-screens-monitor-id}`), but I'd like to first hear from @ggalves about the `displayID` API he was talking about\n\nAnd one last question: does sketchybar use 1-based or 0-based indices?","files":null}]}